WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.940
[Amit Varma]: It is said that shared experiences can bring us closer. By the same token, can shared suffering

00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:15.740
[Amit Varma]: make us more empathetic? There has never been a period of time in our history when so many

00:00:15.740 --> 00:00:19.760
[Amit Varma]: have suffered together. At some point in the last few months, and perhaps in just the last

00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:25.540
[Amit Varma]: few weeks, every family in India has known of loss or grief or anger in some form or

00:00:25.540 --> 00:00:31.160
[Amit Varma]: the other. Every day, anodyne phrases that one just said reflexively have taken on deeper

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:36.500
[Amit Varma]: meaning. These days, when I say, how are you? Or is everything okay? Or take care? I mean

00:00:36.500 --> 00:00:40.980
[Amit Varma]: those words. There is so much bad news around me that I should be numb by now. But I am

00:00:40.980 --> 00:00:46.120
[Amit Varma]: the opposite of numb. Every loss I hear about makes all other losses blaze within me. And

00:00:46.120 --> 00:00:52.040
[Amit Varma]: I see that most people I speak to feel the same. We are alive to the pain of other people.

00:00:52.040 --> 00:00:56.960
[Amit Varma]: We are not islands anymore. And here I must ask the question, what will we do with this

00:00:56.960 --> 00:01:02.280
[Amit Varma]: outpouring of empathy? Instead of just feeling bad for others, is there any way that we can

00:01:02.280 --> 00:01:06.720
[Unknown]: help them?

00:01:06.720 --> 00:01:11.920
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:19.000
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:22.480
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is one of my favorite thinkers in this

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:27.520
[Amit Varma]: country, Ashwin Mahesh. But Ashwin is not just a thinker, he's also a doer. Listeners

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:32.880
[Amit Varma]: of the show will remember him from episode 160, where we spoke about participatory democracy.

00:01:32.880 --> 00:01:37.180
[Amit Varma]: And Ashwin outlined the many different ways in which citizens can empower themselves by

00:01:37.180 --> 00:01:41.600
[Amit Varma]: working with the state. He himself has been at the forefront of much civic activism and

00:01:41.600 --> 00:01:46.160
[Amit Varma]: action and he kicked it into a new gear in this pandemic. There were immediate problems

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:50.700
[Amit Varma]: that needed to be addressed, people needing food, medicine, oxygen. And there were deeper

00:01:50.700 --> 00:01:55.880
[Amit Varma]: problems behind them that Ashwin has already been working to solve for many years now.

00:01:55.880 --> 00:02:00.200
[Amit Varma]: I spoke a few months ago with Ashwin's colleague in Mumbai, Ruben Mascarenhas, one of the founders

00:02:00.200 --> 00:02:05.280
[Amit Varma]: of the Khana Chahiye movement that fed hungry people during the lockdown last year, especially

00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:09.560
[Amit Varma]: the migrant workers abandoned by both their employers and the state. Ruben's been active

00:02:09.560 --> 00:02:13.880
[Amit Varma]: helping people in Mumbai with medicines and beds during the second wave. And Ashwin's

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:20.120
[Amit Varma]: been organising that kind of relief work at scale, so much so that even governments have

00:02:20.120 --> 00:02:25.400
[Amit Varma]: reached out to his network to get things done. I was delighted to have Ashwin on the show

00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:29.800
[Amit Varma]: to chat about his experiences and learnings. And as it happens, there are also threads

00:02:29.800 --> 00:02:35.040
[Amit Varma]: of a continuing discussion here. In my last wildly popular episode with Karthik Muralidharan

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:39.520
[Amit Varma]: on India's healthcare, you might have heard my scepticism about getting the state to do

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:44.760
[Amit Varma]: the few things it should do. To me, society will have to solve its own problems. We cannot

00:02:44.760 --> 00:02:49.360
[Amit Varma]: rely on the dysfunctional state. Karthik argued with me then on the importance of working

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:54.680
[Amit Varma]: with the state and cited Ashwin's words from previous episodes to back up his argument.

00:02:54.680 --> 00:03:00.120
[Amit Varma]: And in this episode, Ashwin carries that argument forward. I love the work both of them do.

00:03:00.120 --> 00:03:04.480
[Amit Varma]: I think it's important. I hope many young people get inspired by them. But before we

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:10.960
[Amit Varma]: get to my conversation with Ashwin, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:13.960
[Amit Varma]: The Second Coming by William Butler Yeats

00:03:13.960 --> 00:03:17.840
[Amit Varma]: Turning and turning in the widening jaya, the falcon cannot hear the falconer. Things

00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:22.880
[Amit Varma]: fall apart, the centre cannot hold. Mere anarchy is loosed upon the world. The blood-drenched

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:28.120
[Amit Varma]: tide is loosed, and everywhere the ceremony of innocence is drowned. The best lack all

00:03:28.120 --> 00:03:33.120
[Amit Varma]: conviction, while the worst are full of passionate intensity.

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:38.040
[Amit Varma]: This poem by Yeats could be about so many things. And most of all, it can be about revolution.

00:03:38.040 --> 00:03:42.960
[Amit Varma]: The centre cannot hold, the people rise up. What was once taken for granted is now washed

00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:45.960
[Amit Varma]: away. Revolutions, both good and bad, have always

00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:50.360
[Amit Varma]: fascinated me. And if you feel that way as well, I have a recommendation for you. Head

